Certainly! Here's a multiple choice question formatted in LaTeX to test knowledge of basic linear algebra concepts:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\textbf{Question:} Given the matrix $A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 2 \\ -3 & 4 \end{bmatrix}$, what is the determinant of $A$?

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(A)] $-10$
    \item[(B)] $10$
    \item[(C)] $-11$
    \item[(D)] $11$
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Solution:}

The determinant of a $2 \times 2$ matrix $A = \begin{bmatrix} a & b \\ c & d \end{bmatrix}$ is calculated using the formula:
\[
\text{det}(A) = ad - bc
\]

For the given matrix $A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 2 \\ -3 & 4 \end{bmatrix}$, we have:
\[
\text{det}(A) = (1)(4) - (2)(-3) = 4 + 6 = 10
\]

Therefore, the correct answer is (B) $10$.

To verify this computation, you can use the following MATLAB code:

\begin{verbatim}
A = [1 2; -3 4];
detA = det(A);
\end{verbatim}

\end{document}
```

This will produce a document with a question, solution, and MATLAB verification code for the determinant of matrix \( A \). The correct answer is (B) \( 10 \).
